value.value: Anatomical region anteriorly located on the body or body part.
Anatomical region posteriorly located on the body or body part.

definition.value: This is an example of a composition of two axis positions.

value.value: The region corresponding to the ventral region of the entity, towards the midline.
An anatomical axis that extends from the center of the body outwards or externally.

definition.value: The medial-external axis could apply to a sphere-shaped body.

value.value: Anatomical surface that is located on the anterior side of the body or body part.
Anatomical surface that is located on the posterior side of the body or body part.
Anatomical surface that is located on the proximal side of the body or body part.

Anatomical surface that is located on the ventral side of the body or body part.
A flat 2D plane intersecting an anatomical continuant, dividing it into two adjacent portions.

definition.value: These anatomical sections are applicable to most bilaterally symmetrical animals, but bipedal animals such as humans have more complex usage of these terms. For example, in post-embryonic humans a coronal plane is vertical and a transverse plane is horizontal, but for embryos and quadrupeds a coronal plane is horizontal and a transverse plane is vertical.

value.value: Anatomical plane that divides a bilateral body into left and right parts, not necessarily of even size.
An axis that extends from the center of organism to one or other side.

definition.value: Properly, the ML axis is a half axis; practically, its usage is less clumsy and less linguistically biased than "left-right". The terms may still be used relatively to describe locations along the LR axis. The gills are medial to the operculum, but lateral to the heart.

value.value: A part of a cellular organism that is either an immaterial entity or a material entity with granularity above the level of a protein complex.  Or, a substance produced by a cellular organism with granularity above the level of a protein complex.
Biological entity that is either an individual member of a biological species or constitutes the structural organization of an individual member of a biological species.

definition.value: Following BFO, material anatomical entities may have immaterial parts (the lumen of your stomach is part of your stomach).  The granularity limit follows the limits set by the Gene Ontology on the granularity limit for GO:cellular_component. Note that substances produced by an organism (sweat, feaces, urine) do not need to be part of an organism to qualify as an anatomical structure.

value.value: Material anatomical entity that is a single connected structure with inherent 3D shape generated by coordinated expression of the organism's own genome.

definition.value: Note that the definition does not say 'generated exclusively by the co-ordinated expression of the organism's own genome', so this is still valid for cases where normal morphogenesis requires the actions of a facultative symbiont, or some looser dependency such as the a requirement for the presence of gut flora for normal gut development.

value.value: An anatomical entity that has mass.
An anatomical entity that has no mass.

definition.value: Anatomical entity that has no mass.

value.value: A one dimensional, immaterial anatomical entity.
A non-material anatomical entity of two dimensions. Anatomical boundaries are contiguous structures.

definition.value: A fasciculated bundle of neuron projections (GO:0043005), largely or completely lacking synapses.
Material anatomical entity that is a member of an individual species or is a viral or viroid particle.
An anatomical structure that has more than one cell as a part.
Elementary particle not affected by the strong force having a spin 1/2, a negative elementary charge and a rest mass of 0.000548579903(13) u, or 0.51099906(15) MeV.
A class of carbonyl compound encompassing dicarboxylic acids and any derivatives obtained by substitution of either one or both of the carboxy hydrogens.
A carbohydrate acid derivative anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy groups of hyaluronic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
Any steroid that has beta-configuration at position 5.
A Bronsted acid derived from one or more inorganic compounds. Inorganic acids (also known as mineral acids) form hydrons and conjugate base ions when dissolved in water.

Any member of a group of hydroxy steroids occuring in bile, where they are present as the sodium salts of their amides with glycine or taurine. In mammals bile acids almost invariably have 5beta-configuration, while in lower vertebrates, some bile acids, known as allo-bile acids, have 5alpha-configuration.
Any main group molecular entity that is gaseous at standard temperature and pressure (STP; 0degreeC and 100 kPa).

An antigenic epitope recognized by an anti-bilirubin monoclonal antibody designated 24G7. A substructure of bilirubin IXalpha, it is the region containing the oxo group at C-1, the methyl group at C-2, C-(4, 5, 6, 9), and N-21 and -22.
A molecular entity that can accept an electron, a pair of electrons, an atom or a group from another molecular entity.
Actylcholine is an ester of acetic acid and choline, which acts as a neurotransmitter.
A simple monocarboxylic acid containing two carbons.
Aldehydic parent sugars (polyhydroxy aldehydes H[CH(OH)]nC(=O)H, n >= 2) and their intramolecular hemiacetals.
A peptide containing ten or more amino acid residues.
A nucleobase-containing molecular entity with a polymeric structure comprised of a linear sequence of 13 or more nucleotide residues.
An azane that consists of a single nitrogen atom covelently bonded to three hydrogen atoms.
A sulfur oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of both OH groups of sulfuric acid.

A mucopolysaccharide composed of N-acetylglucosamine and glucuronic acid subunits. It is found in the connective tissues of vertebrates. A principal constituent of the extracellular matrix (ECM), it mediates the growth and metastasis of tumour cells.
A naturally occurring polypeptide synthesized at the ribosome.
